[{"id":"VR854849","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\">\n<div class=\"title\"><p class=\"title_line passage-title\">Percentage of Children Diagnosed with ADHD</p></div>\n<img alt=\"The figure shows a map of the United States titled “Percentage of Children Diagnosed with ADHD.” A key indicates that each state falls into one of the following categories: 16%, 14%, 12%, 10%, 8%, 6%. The states fall into the categories as follows. 16%: Louisiana. 14%: West Virginia. 12%: New Hampshire, Delaware, Kentucky, North Carolina, Georgia, and Mississippi. 10%: Connecticut, South Carolina, Indiana, Tennessee, Alabama, Wisconsin, Iowa, Missouri, Arkansas, Kansas, and Oklahoma. 8%: Vermont, Rhode Island, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Florida, Illinois, North Dakota, Montana, Idaho, Oregon, Utah, Arizona, New Mexico, Texas, Alaska, and Hawaii. 6%: Maine, Massachusetts, New York, New Jersey, Maryland, Virginia, Minnesota, South Dakota, Nebraska, Wyoming, Colorado, Washington, Nevada, and California.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR854849.g02.svg\"/>\n</div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following is supported by the data in the provided map of ADHD diagnoses?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR854849_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">States in western United States do not believe ADHD is an actual disorder.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">States with higher population have higher percentages of diagnosed ADHD in children.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Children in the Northwest of the United States are diagnosed at a higher rate than those of the Southeast.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Possible causes of ADHD may be related to environmental factors like geography.</p>"],"answer":3}]